SIMPLE: polemic
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Polemic
<hw>Po*lem"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ warlike,
fr.<?/ war: cf. F. <ets>pol⟦eacute⟧mique</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Of or pertaining to controversy; maintaining, or involving,
controversy; controversial; disputative; <as>as, a <ex>polemic</ex>
discourse or essay; <ex>polemic</ex> theology.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Engaged in, or addicted to, polemics, or to
controversy; disputations; <as>as, a <ex>polemic</ex> writer</as>.</def>
<rj><au>South.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Polemic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Polemic
<hw>Po*lem"ic</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who writes in
support of one opinion, doctrine, or system, in opposition to another;
one skilled in polemics; a controversialist; a disputant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sarcasms and invectives of the young <qex>polemic</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A polemic argument or controversy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Polemical</ent>⟦br⟧
